      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During that time, urban planners and real estate agents framed redlining as a necessary measure to maintain \"residential stability\" and \"property values\" in predominantly white neighborhoods. They argued that by limiting minority homebuyers to high-risk areas, they were actually helping to maintain a stable and desirable living environment for existing residents. This was often justified through the lens of \"urban planning theory,\" which emphasized the importance of maintaining \"homogeneous\" neighborhoods and preventing the \"mixing of races\" that was seen as a threat to social cohesion. By framing redlining as a means of protecting property values and maintaining stability, proponents could present it as a rational and economically sound policy, rather than a racist tool for exclusion.",
